This file contians Syntax in java map to begin with.


1.Creating a Map

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class MapExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Map<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();

        map.put(1, "One");
        map.put(2, "Two");
        map.put(3, "Three");

        System.out.println(map);  
    }
}


put(key, value) → adds or updates a key-value pair.


2.Accessing Values
System.out.println(map.get(2)); // Output: "Two"
System.out.println(map.get(4)); // Output: null (key doesn't exist)

get(key) → returns the value for that key.
If the key isn’t in the map, it returns null.


4️.Checking if a Key Exists
if (map.containsKey(1)) {
    System.out.println("Key 1 exists!");
}
containsKey(key) → returns true if the key is in the map.

5️.Iterating Over a Map
Option 1: Using entrySet()
for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : map.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " -> " + entry.getValue());
}
entrySet() gives a set of key-value pairs.
entry.getKey() → key, entry.getValue() → value

Option 2: Using keySet()
for (Integer key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key + " -> " + map.get(key));
}
keySet() gives all keys, then you can get(key) to access the value.

5. Removing a Key
map.remove(2);  // Removes key 2 and its value
